      <article class="article">
        <div class="kicker">Markets and Finance</div>

        <h2 class="headline">Speed Limits Hurt Markets</h2>

        <p class="deck">
          Attempts to slow electronic trading are sold as fairness reforms. In practice, they weaken liquidity and raise the cost of getting a trade done.
        </p>

        <div class="meta">
          <span><strong>By</strong> The Academic Edge Desk</span>
          <span class="dot"></span>
          <span>6 min read</span>
          <span class="dot"></span>
          <span>Updated Feb. 8, 2026</span>
        </div>

        <div class="body">
          <p class="lead">
            Speed, long criticized as a source of market unfairness, is a central driver of liquidity in modern electronic markets. Faster high-frequency market makers quote tighter prices, execute more trades, and improve overall market quality, while artificial speed limits weaken liquidity and widen spreads.
          </p>

          <p>
            In today’s markets, most liquidity is supplied by a small number of high-speed traders who continuously post and update quotes. Speed allows these traders to revise prices quickly, manage inventory risk, and reduce losses from stale quotes when prices move. As speed increases, market makers are willing to quote more aggressively, narrowing bid-ask spreads and increasing execution rates.
          </p>

          <p>
            When speed is reduced, the opposite occurs. A natural experiment on NYSE American provides clear evidence. In 2017 the exchange imposed a 350-microsecond delay on all orders, slowing high-frequency traders. Quoted spreads widened, depth at the best prices declined, fill rates fell, and order cancellations increased relative to other exchanges. In 2019, when the delay was removed, these effects reversed. Liquidity improved and spreads tightened, closely tracking changes in trading speed.
          </p>

          <p>
            Faster trading does enable some price discrimination against impatient investors, as market makers can anticipate order flow. But this cost is outweighed by higher liquidity provision. Even traders who occasionally face worse prices benefit from faster markets through quicker execution and lower average trading costs.
          </p>

          <p>
            The evidence cuts against the case for speed bumps and latency floors. Slowing markets reduces the incentive to supply liquidity without eliminating informational advantages. Markets function better when speed is allowed to discipline risk, tighten pricing, and support continuous liquidity provision. Policies that restrain speed in the name of fairness risk degrading the quality of markets investors rely on.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rule">
